{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"B\n    \n      B — Typed control-plane core  (Recommended)\n      What it is: The core API becomes a typed contract across 4 dimensions — inputs (command IR), observation (perceive primitives), errors (result values), trace (span stream) — carried over one persistent bidirectional channel to a THIN on-device agent. Sync is event-driven (device pushes \"UI changed\" / \"idle\") plus actionability checks; black-box by default with an OPTIONAL gray-box idle SDK. YAML / JSON / TS are persistence adapters that compile to the command IR. The batch runner is just one consumer; agents call perceive-act primitives directly via MCP.\n      \n        \n          Pros\n          \n            Fixes the root cause — event-driven sync kills poll-and-diff → fast + reliable\n            Genuinely agent-native (fine-grained perceive-act + structured trace for self-correction)\n            Clean separation (control plane vs persistence vs runner) = flexible, simple, clear\n            YAML survives as the strongest persistence adapter (the moat)\n            Thin on-device agent is far less brittle and easy to evolve\n          \n        \n        \n          Cons\n          \n            Largest effort\n            Requires rebuilding the on-device agents + transport\n            A new wire protocol to design and version\n            Migration must protect the installed YAML base and the 4 existing consumers","choice":"b","id":null,"timestamp":1779986249784}
